Encouraged by their unique 2D structure, the as-synthesized Ni-MOF and Ni-MOF/C-CNTs hybrid was directly used as active components to fabricate electrodes. The electrochemical performances were systematically investigated in the three-electrode system by using 3 M KOH as an aqueous electrolyte. The CV curves of Ni-MOF and a series of Ni-MOF/C-CNTs hybrids are displayed in Fig. 4a. A pair of redox peaks along with the clear potential separations could be identified in all CV curves, which is an indicative feature of battery-type electrode. This typical characteristic is generally considered as the reversible transformation between Ni(II) and Ni(III) on account of faradaic redox reaction under the presence of OH−, which can be described as Eqs. 1 and 2 [48, 55, 56]:1NiII+OH-↔NiIIOH+e-\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
